ural turn in social sciences, an approach that assumes that violence is filled with meaning, which is “culturally constructed, discursively mediated, symbolically saturated, and ritually regulated.” The author argues that pogroms in Lithuania instead followed a communal pattern of ethnic violence and was very different from deadly pogroms in other parts of the Russian Empire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aAntisemitismzLithuaniaxHistoryy19th century. 0aJewszLithuaniaxHistoryy19th century. 0aLithuania--Ethnic relations. 7aRELIGION / Religious Intolerance, Persecution & Conflict.2bisacsh  aAntisemitism, Ethnic relations, History, Jews, Political persecution, Lithuania, Belarus.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311078054340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633860946423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789633860946/original  a978-3-11-078054-3  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK